The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, April 10: Indian Hotels Company has revised the closing date of its rights issue by nine days to April 24 and has deferred the issue of warrants by a year because of volatile market conditions. Indian Hotels had issued 120.6 million shares to its shareholders at Rs 70 per share in a ratio of one share for every five held. The company also issued 6 per cent non-convertible debentures at Rs 100 each with detachable warrants convertible into equity at Rs 150 in September 2008. The warrant issue will open on September 1 and close on September 30, 2009.                            
	 Moscow, April 10: The Moscow Bank of Reconstruction and Development (mbrd) said it was in talks with ICICI Bank for a tieup to sell products such as mortgage loans. The deal may be finalised soon and we feel this will be a win-win situation for both the banks, mbrd chairman Sergey Zaytsev said.                            
	 Mumbai, April 10: The National Commodity amp; Derivatives Exchange has launched its futures contract for certified emission reduction.                            
	 Mumbai, April 10: Chennai-based Orchid Chemicals has formed a wholly owned subsidiary in Japan. The new entity, Orchid Pharma Japan, will be headquartered in Tokyo.                            
	 Mumbai, April 10: Private sector lender Development Credit Bank (DCB) will consider merger possibilities after 2009 when the countrys banking sector is expected to be opened up for foreign players, chairman Nasser Munjee said.                            
	 New Delhi, April 10: The government will appoint an independent regulator for the aviation industry by October this year, K. N. Srivastava, secretary in the civil aviation ministry, said.                            
	 Durban, April 10: Tata Steel has commissioned the first furnace at its Richards Bay ferrochrome plant in Durban. The plant is the first project built by the Tatas outside india.                                                                                                                         
